    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Feature already in Vim?\r\n\r\nno\r\n\r\n### Feature description\r\n\r\nmy usecase is:\r\n```\r\n$ nvim\r\n:vs\r\n:sp\r\n<c-w>J\r\n```\r\nso now there are three split windows (winnr: 1, 2, 3), and 3 is the current window. when i close 3, the cursor will go to 1, but actually 3's previous window (`<c-w>p`) is 2.\r\n\r\nthis is always not an expected behavior to me, i once opened [an issue for this in trouble.nvim](https://github.com/folke/trouble.nvim/issues/189).\r\nof course, i can use a simple autocmd to do this, but i'm wondering if this could be a good default to be added to nvim\r\n```\r\n  vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"WinClosed\", {\r\n    nested = true,\r\n    callback = function(args)\r\n      if api.nvim_get_current_win() ~= tonumber(args.match) then return end\r\n      vim.cmd.wincmd \"p\"\r\n    end,\r\n  })\r\n```\r\n\r\nupdate 1: fixed a fatal error: using WinLeave instead of WinClosed before\r\nupdate 2: check if it's a focused window that being closed",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "That autocmd sure looks trivial, so if it is reliable I think we should instead document it at `:help CTRL-W_p`. Similar for `:help g<Tab>`. And add these new tags (\"previous\" is overloaded in the help docs so it's hard to find info about this):\r\n\r\n```\r\n*previous-win*\r\n*recent-win*\r\n*previous-tabpage*\r\n*recent-tabpage*\r\n```",
